div.font: Economic growth drives GDP and hence the purchasing power of the household. That increases the demands of real estate prices.
Similar follows in economic downturn. The demands for real estate decrease and hence prices tend to decrease

div.div: Decrease in unemployment increase the purchasing power of the household and hence drives the demand of real estate higher.
When unemployement rates are high, the demands for the real estate also decrease.

div.div: Even though the housing market may appear sluggish, prime locations in posh neighbourhoods tend to have higher average prices because of their demands. Location of a property can drive the price up or down

div.div: With about 60% of the American population between 20 to 60 years old, the population in the workforce is strong and comprises of an amployable age group. This impacts the economy positively and hence drives the demand for the housing sector. With the population growing older and passing the retirement age of 60, the purchase power of the population will decrease.

div.div: Government policies that encourage growth and investment increase the interests of builders and developers. Hence the investment in real estate increase with increase in favourable policies and subsidies. The opposite is true for the policies that limit investment in real estate. The supply decrease henceforth.

div.div: The resources can be divided into multiple categories.
Resources in time measure the time taken for the construction. The ease of construction and maintenance leads to less labour and building costs
Cost constraints point to the capital required to build the certain project,the wages and the cost of materials incurred. All of these impact the ROI of the project
Labour Resources point out the wages of skilled labour to be employed and the maintenance cost of the proposed project
